{"text": "1.3 Classification of Crystalline Solids

      In Section 1.2, we have learnt about amorphous substances and that they have only short range order.", "fibs": ["Section"]}
{"text": "However, most of the solid substances are crystalline in nature.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "For example, all the metallic elements like iron, copper and silver; non-metallic elements like sulphur, phosphorus and iodine and compounds like sodium chloride, zinc sulphide and naphthalene form crystalline solids.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The method depends on the purpose in hand.", "fibs": ["method"]}
{"text": "Here, we will classify crystalline solids on the basis of nature of intermolecular forces or bonds that hold the constituent particles together.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
{"text": "These are — (i) Van der waals forces; (ii) Ionic bonds; (iii) Covalent bonds; and (iv) Metallic bonds.", "fibs": ["—"]}
{"text": "On this basis, crystalline solids are classified into four categories viz., molecular, ionic, metallic and covalent solids.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
{"text": "1.3.1 Molecular Solids


      Molecules are the constituent particles of molecular solids.", "fibs": ["constituent"]}
{"text": "These are further sub divided into the following categories:

(i) Non polar Molecular Solids: They comprise either atoms, for example, argon and helium or the molecules formed by non polar covalent bonds, for example, H2, Cl2 and I2.", "fibs": ["sub"]}
{"text": "In these solids, the atoms or molecules are held by weak dispersion forces or London forces about which you have learnt in Class XI.", "fibs": ["dispersion"]}
{"text": "These solids are soft and non-conductors of electricity.", "fibs": ["electricity"]}
{"text": "They have low melting points and are usually in liquid or gaseous state at room temperature and pressure.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "(ii) Polar Molecular Solids: The molecules of substances like HCl, SO2, etc.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "are formed by polar covalent bonds.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "These solids are soft and non-conductors of electricity.", "fibs": ["electricity"]}
{"text": "Their melting points are higher than those of non polar molecular solids yet most of these are gases or liquids under room temperature and pressure.", "fibs": ["room"]}
{"text": "Solid SO2 and solid NH3 are some examples of such solids.", "fibs": ["SO2"]}
{"text": "(iii) Hydrogen Bonded Molecular Solids: The molecules of such solids contain polar covalent bonds between H and F, O or N atoms.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "Strong hydrogen bonding binds molecules of such solids like H2O (ice).", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "They are non-conductors of electricity.", "fibs": ["electricity"]}
{"text": "Generally they are volatile liquids or soft solids under room temperature and pressure.", "fibs": ["room"]}
{"text": "1.3.2 Ionic Solids
Ions are the constituent particles of ionic solids.", "fibs": ["constituent"]}
{"text": "Such solids are formed by the three dimensional arrangements of cations and anions bound by strong coulombic (electrostatic) forces.", "fibs": ["coulombic"]}
{"text": "These solids are hard and brittle in nature.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "Since the ions are not free to move about, they are electrical insulators in the solid state.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "However, in the molten state or when dissolved in water, the ions become free to move about and they conduct electricity.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "1.3.3 Metallic Solids
Metals are orderly collection of positive ions surrounded by and held together by a sea of free electrons.", "fibs": ["collection"]}
{"text": "These electrons are mobile and are evenly spread out throughout the crystal.", "fibs": ["spread"]}
{"text": "Each metal atom contributes one or more electrons towards this sea of mobile electrons.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "These free and mobile electrons are responsible for high electrical and thermal conductivity of metals.", "fibs": ["conductivity"]}
{"text": "When an electric field is applied, these electrons flow through the network of positive ions.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Similarly, when heat is supplied to one portion of a metal, the thermal energy is uniformly spread throughout by free electrons.", "fibs": ["heat"]}
{"text": "Another important characteristic of metals is their lustre and colour in certain cases.", "fibs": ["lustre"]}
{"text": "This is also due to the presence of free electrons in them.", "fibs": ["presence"]}
{"text": "Metals are highly malleable and ductile.", "fibs": ["ductile"]}
{"text": "1.3.4 Covalent or Network Solids
A wide variety of crystalline solids of non-metals result from the formation of covalent bonds between adjacent atoms throughout the crystal.", "fibs": ["variety"]}
{"text": "They are also called giant molecules.", "fibs": ["giant"]}
{"text": "Covalent bonds are strong and directional in nature, therefore atoms are held very strongly at their positions.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "They are insulators and do not conduct electricity.", "fibs": ["conduct"]}
{"text": "Diamond (Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.3) and silicon carbide are typical examples of such solids.", "fibs": ["silicon"]}
{"text": "Although Graphite (Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.4) also belongs to this class of crystals, but it is soft and is a conductor of electricity.", "fibs": ["class"]}
{"text": "Its exceptional properties are due to its typical structure.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "Carbon atoms are arranged in different layers and each atom is covalently bonded to three of its neighbouring atoms in the same layer.", "fibs": ["atom"]}
{"text": "The fourth valence electron of each atom is present between different layers and is free to move about.", "fibs": ["valence"]}
{"text": "These free electrons make graphite a good conductor of electricity.", "fibs": ["graphite"]}
{"text": "Different layers can slide one over the other.", "fibs": ["slide"]}
{"text": "This makes graphite a soft solid and a good solid lubricant.", "fibs": ["graphite"]}
