{"text": "1.4 Crystal Lattices and Unit Cells

        You must have noticed that when tiles are placed to cover a floor, a repeated pattern is generated.", "fibs": ["Unit"]}
{"text": "If after setting tiles on floor we mark a point at same location in all the tiles (e.g.", "fibs": ["floor"]}
{"text": "Centre of the tile) and see the marked positions only ignoring the tiles, we obtain a set of points.", "fibs": ["tile"]}
{"text": "This set of points is the scaffolding on which pattern has been developed by placing tiles.", "fibs": ["scaffolding"]}
{"text": "This scaffolding is a space lattice on which two-dimensional pattern has been developed by placing structural units on its set of points (i.e.", "fibs": ["scaffolding"]}
{"text": "tile in this case).", "fibs": ["tile"]}
{"text": "The structural unit is called basis or motif.", "fibs": ["unit"]}
{"text": "When motifs are placed on points in space lattice, a pattern is generated.", "fibs": ["space"]}
{"text": "In crystal structure, motif is a molecule, atom or ion.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "A space lattice,also called a crystal lattice, is the pattern of points representing the locations of these motifs.", "fibs": ["space"]}
{"text": "In other words, space lattice is an abstract scaffolding for crystal structure.", "fibs": ["space"]}
{"text": "When we place motifs in an identical manner on points of space lattice, we get crystal structure.", "fibs": ["place"]}
