{"text": "The crystal structure is obtained by associating structurral motifs with lattice points.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "Each repeated basis or motif has same structure and same spacial orientation as other one in a crystal.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
{"text": "The environment of each motif is same throughout the crystal except for on surface.", "fibs": ["environment"]}
{"text": "Following are the characteristics of a crystal lattice:
(a) Each point in a lattice is called lattice point or lattice site.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "(b) Each point in a crystal lattice represents one constituent particle which may be an atom, a molecule (group of atoms) or an ion.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "(c) Lattice points are joined by straight lines to bring out the geometry of the lattice.", "fibs": ["geometry"]}
{"text": "We need only a small part of the space lattice of a crystal to spacify crystal completely.", "fibs": ["need"]}
{"text": "This small part is called unit cell.", "fibs": ["part"]}
{"text": "One can choose unit cell in many ways.", "fibs": ["unit"]}
{"text": "Normally that cell is chosen which has perpendicular sides of shortest length and one can construct entire crystal by translational displacement of the unit cell in three dimensions.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
