{"text": "1.6 Close Packed Structures
In solids, the constituent particles are close-packed, leaving the minimum vacant space.", "fibs": ["constituent"]}
{"text": "Let us consider the constituent particles as identical hard spheres and build up the three-dimensional structure in three steps.", "fibs": ["constituent"]}
{"text": "(a) Close Packing in One Dimension
There is only one way of arranging spheres in a one-dimensional close packed structure, that is to arrange them in a row and touching each other (Fig.", "fibs": ["way"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.17: Close packing of spheres in one dimension
In this arrangement, each sphere is in contact with two of its neighbours.", "fibs": ["dimension"]}
{"text": "The number of nearest neighbours of a particle is called its coordination number.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Thus, in one dimensional close packed arrangement, the coordination number is 2.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "(b) Close Packing in Two Dimensions
Two dimensional close packed structure can be generated by stacking (placing) the rows of close packed spheres.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "(i) The second row may be placed in contact with the first one such that the spheres of the second row are exactly above those of the first row.", "fibs": ["row"]}
{"text": "If we call the first row as ‘A’ type row, the second row being exactly the same as the first one, is also of ‘A’ type.", "fibs": ["row"]}
{"text": "Similarly, we may place more rows to obtain AAA type of arrangement as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["place"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.18: (a) Square close packing (b) hexagonal close packing of spheres in two dimensions





In this arrangement, each sphere is in contact with four of its neighbours.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "Thus, the two dimensional coordination number is 4.", "fibs": ["coordination"]}
{"text": "Also, if the centres of these 4 immediate neighbouring spheres are joined, a square is formed.", "fibs": ["square"]}
{"text": "Hence this packing is called square close packing in two dimensions.", "fibs": ["square"]}
{"text": "(ii) The second row may be placed above the first one in a staggered manner such that its spheres fit in the depressions of the first row.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "If the arrangement of spheres in the first row is called ‘A’ type, the one in the second row is different and may be called ‘B’ type.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "When the third row is placed adjacent to the second in staggered manner, its spheres are aligned with those of the first layer.", "fibs": ["row"]}
{"text": "Hence this layer is also of ‘A’ type.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "The spheres of similarly placed fourth row will be aligned with those of the second row (‘B’ type).", "fibs": ["row"]}
{"text": "Hence this arrangement is of ABAB type.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "In this arrangement there is less free space and this packing is more efficient than the square close packing.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "Each sphere is in contact with six of its neighbours and the two dimensional coordination number is 6.", "fibs": ["sphere"]}
{"text": "The centres of these six spheres are at the corners of a regular hexagon (Fig.", "fibs": ["hexagon"]}
{"text": "1.18 b) hence this packing is called two dimensional hexagonal close-packing.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "It can be seen in Figure 1.18 (b) that in this layer there are some voids (empty spaces).", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "These are triangular in shape.", "fibs": ["shape"]}
{"text": "In one row, the apex of the triangles are pointing upwards and in the next layer downwards.", "fibs": ["row"]}
{"text": "In the last Section, we discussed close packing in two dimensions which can be of two types; square close-packed and hexagonal close-packed.", "fibs": ["Section"]}
{"text": "(i) Three-dimensional close packing forms two-dimensional square close-packed layers: While placing the second square close-packed layer above the first we follow the same rule that was followed when one row was placed adjacent to the other.", "fibs": ["square"]}
{"text": "The second layer is placed over the first layer such that the spheres of the upper layer are exactly above those of the first layer.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "In this arrangement spheres of both the layers are perfectly aligned horizontally as well as vertically as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "Similarly, we may place more layers one above the other.", "fibs": ["place"]}
{"text": "If the arrangement of spheres in the first layer is called ‘A’ type, all the layers have the same arrangement.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "Thus this lattice has AAA.... type pattern.", "fibs": ["lattice"]}
{"text": "The lattice thus generated is the simple cubic lattice, and its unit cell is the primitive cubic unit cell (See Fig.", "fibs": ["lattice"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.19: Simple cubic lattice formed by A A A .... arrangement
(ii) Three dimensional close packing from two dimensional hexagonal close packed layers: Three dimensional close packed structure can be generated by placing layers one over the other.", "fibs": ["lattice"]}
{"text": "(a) Placing second layer over the first layer
Let us take a two dimensional hexagonal close packed layer ‘A’ and place a similar layer above it such that the spheres of the second layer are placed in the depressions of the first layer.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "Since the spheres of the two layers are aligned differently, let us call the second layer as B.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "It can be observed from Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.20 that all the triangular voids of the first layer are not covered by the spheres of the second layer.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "This gives rise to different arrangements.", "fibs": ["rise"]}
{"text": "Wherever a sphere of the second layer is above the void of the first layer (or vice versa) a tetrahedral void is formed.", "fibs": ["sphere"]}
{"text": "These voids are called tetrahedral voids because a tetrahedron is formed when the centres of these four spheres are joined.", "fibs": ["tetrahedron"]}
{"text": "Theyhave been marked as ‘T’ in Fig.", "fibs": ["‘"]}
{"text": "One such void has been shown separately in Fig.", "fibs": ["void"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.20: A stack of two layers of close packed spheres and voids generated in them.", "fibs": ["stack"]}
{"text": "T = Tetrahedral void; O = Octahedral void






Fig 1.21 Tetrahedral and octahedral voids (a) top view (b) exploded side view and (c) geometrical shape of the void.", "fibs": ["void"]}
{"text": "At other places, the triangular voids in the second layer are above the triangular voids in the first layer, and the triangular shapes of these do not overlap.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "One of them has the apex of the triangle pointing upwards and the other downwards.", "fibs": ["apex"]}
{"text": "These voids have been marked as ‘O’ in Fig.", "fibs": ["‘"]}
{"text": "One such void has been shown separately in Fig.", "fibs": ["void"]}
{"text": "The number of these two types of voids depend upon the number of close packed spheres.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Let the number of close packed spheres be N, then:
The number of octahedral voids generated = N
The number of tetrahedral voids generated = 2N
(b) Placing third layer over the second layer





When third layer is placed over the second, there are two possibilities.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "(i) Covering Tetrahedral Voids: Tetrahedral voids of the second layer may be covered by the spheres of the third layer.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "In this case, the spheres of the third layer are exactly aligned with those of the first layer.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Thus, the pattern of spheres is repeated in alternate layers.", "fibs": ["pattern"]}
{"text": "This pattern is often written as ABAB ....... pattern.", "fibs": ["pattern"]}
{"text": "This structure is called hexagonal close packed (hcp) structure (Fig.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "This sort of arrangement of atoms is found in many metals like magnesium and zinc.", "fibs": ["sort"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.22  (a) Hexagonal cubic close-packing exploded view showing stacking of layers of spheres  (b) four layers stacked in each case and (c) geometry of packing.", "fibs": ["view"]}
{"text": "(ii) Covering Octahedral Voids: The third layer may be placed above the second layer in a manner such that its spheres cover the octahedral voids.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "When placed in this manner, the spheres of the third layer are not aligned with those of either the first or the second layer.", "fibs": ["manner"]}
{"text": "This arrangement is called ‘C’ type.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "Only when fourth layer is placed, its spheres are aligned with those of the first layer as shown in Figs.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "This pattern of layers is often written as ABCABC ...........", "fibs": ["pattern"]}
{"text": "This structure is called cubic close packed (ccp) or face-centred cubic (fcc) structure.", "fibs": ["structure"]}
{"text": "Metals such as copper and silver crystallise in this structure.", "fibs": ["copper"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.23 (a) ABCABC... arrangement of layers when octahedral void is covered (b) fragment of structure formed by this arrangement resulting in cubic closed packed (ccp) or face centred cubic (fcc) structure.", "fibs": ["ABCABC"]}
{"text": "Both these types of close packing are highly efficient and 74% space in the crystal is filled.", "fibs": ["space"]}
{"text": "In either of them, each sphere is in contact with twelve spheres.", "fibs": ["sphere"]}
{"text": "Thus, the coordination number is 12 in either of these two structures.", "fibs": ["coordination"]}
{"text": "1.6.1 Formula of a Compound and Number of Voids Filled
Earlier in the section, we have learnt that when particles are close-packed resulting in either ccp or hcp structure, two types of voids are generated.", "fibs": ["Formula"]}
{"text": "While the number of octahedral voids present in a lattice is equal to the number of close packed particles, the number of tetrahedral voids generated is twice this number.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "In ionic solids, the bigger ions (usually anions) form the close packed structure and the smaller ions (usually cations) occupy the voids.", "fibs": ["form"]}
{"text": "If the latter ion is small enough then tetrahedral voids are occupied, if bigger, then octahedral voids.", "fibs": ["latter"]}
{"text": "In a given compound, the fraction of octahedral or tetrahedral voids that are occupied, depends upon the chemical formula of the compound, as can be seen from the following examples.", "fibs": ["compound"]}
{"text": "Example 1.1



A compound is formed by two elements X and Y.", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "Atoms of the element Y (as anions) make ccp and those of the element X (as cations) occupy all the octahedral voids.", "fibs": ["element"]}
{"text": "What is the formula of the compound?", "fibs": ["formula"]}
{"text": "Solution
The ccp lattice is formed by the element Y.", "fibs": ["ccp"]}
{"text": "The number of octahedral voids generated would be equal to the number of atoms of Y present in it.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Since all the octahedral voids are occupied by the atoms of X, their number would also be equal to that of the element Y.", "fibs": ["X"]}
{"text": "Thus, the atoms of elements X and Y are present in equal numbers or 1:1 ratio.", "fibs": ["X"]}
{"text": "Therefore, the formula of the compound is XY.", "fibs": ["formula"]}
{"text": "Example 1.2
Atoms of element B form hcp lattice and those of the element A occupy 2/3rd of tetrahedral voids.", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "What is the formula of the compound formed by the elements A and B?", "fibs": ["formula"]}
{"text": "Solution
The number of tetrahedral voids formed is equal to twice the number of atoms of element B and only 2/3rd of these are occupied by the atoms of element A.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Hence the ratio of the number of atoms of A and B is 2 × (2/3):1 or 4:3 and the formula of the compound is A4B3.", "fibs": ["ratio"]}
{"text": "Let us take ccp (or fcc) structure and locate these voids in it.", "fibs": ["ccp"]}
