{"text": "1.9 Imperfections in Solids






Although crystalline solids have short range as well as long range order in the arrangement of their constituent particles, yet crystals are not perfect.", "fibs": ["range"]}
{"text": "Usually a solid consists of an aggregate of large number of small crystals.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "This happens when crystallisation process occurs at fast or moderate rate.", "fibs": ["crystallisation"]}
{"text": "Single crystals are formed when the process of crystallisation occurs at extremely slow rate.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "The defects are basically irregularities in the arrangement of constituent particles.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "Broadly speaking, the defects are of two types, namely, point defects andline defects.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "Point defects are the irregularities or deviations from ideal arrangement around a point or an atom in a crystalline substance, whereas the line defects are the irregularities or deviations from ideal arrangement in entire rows of lattice points.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "These irregularities are called crystal defects.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "We shall confine our discussion to point defects only.", "fibs": ["discussion"]}
{"text": "1.9.1 Types of Point Defects










          Point defects can be classified into three types : (i) stoichiometric defects (ii) impurity defects and (iii) non-stoichiometric defects.", "fibs": ["stoichiometric"]}
{"text": "(a) Stoichiometric Defects
These are the point defects that do not disturb the stoichiometry of the solid.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "Basically these are of two types, vacancy defects and interstitial defects.", "fibs": ["vacancy"]}
{"text": "(i) Vacancy Defect: When some of the lattice sites are vacant, the crystal is said to have vacancy defect (Fig.", "fibs": ["Vacancy"]}
{"text": "This results in decrease in density of the substance.", "fibs": ["decrease"]}
{"text": "This defect can also develop when a substance is heated.", "fibs": ["defect"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.27: Vacancy defects

(ii) Interstitial Defect: When some constituent particles (atoms or molecules) occupy an interstitial site, the crystal is said to have interstitial defect (Fig.", "fibs": ["Vacancy"]}
{"text": "1.28).", "fibs": ["1.28)"]}
{"text": "This defect increases the density of the substance.", "fibs": ["defect"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.28: Interstitial defects



            Vacancy and interstitial defects as explained above can be shown by non-ionic solids.", "fibs": ["Vacancy"]}
{"text": "Ionic solids must always maintain electrical neutrality.", "fibs": ["neutrality"]}
{"text": "Rather than simple vacancy or interstitial defects, they show these defects as Frenkel and Schottky defects.", "fibs": ["vacancy"]}
{"text": "(iii) Frenkel Defect: This defect is shown by ionic solids.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "The smaller ion (usually cation) is dislocated from its normal site to an interstitial site (Fig.", "fibs": ["ion"]}
{"text": "It creates avacancy defect at its original site and an interstitial defect at its new location.", "fibs": ["avacancy"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.29: Frenkel defects

Frenkel defect is also called dislocation defect.", "fibs": ["defect"]}
{"text": "It does not change the density of the solid.", "fibs": ["change"]}
{"text": "Frenkel defect is shown by ionic substance in which there is a large difference in the size of ions, for example, ZnS, AgCl, AgBr and AgI due to small size of Zn2+ and Ag+ ions.", "fibs": ["defect"]}
{"text": "(iv) Schottky Defect: It is basically a vacancy defect in ionic solids.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "In order to maintain electrical neutrality, the number of missing cations and anions are equal (Fig.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.30: Schottky defects




Like simple vacancy defect, Schottky defect also decreases the density of the substance.", "fibs": ["vacancy"]}
{"text": "Number of such defects in ionic solids is quite significant.", "fibs": ["Number"]}
{"text": "For example, in NaCl there are approximately 106 Schottky pairs per cm3 at room temperature.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "In 1 cm3 there are about 1022 ions.", "fibs": ["cm3"]}
{"text": "Thus, there is one Schottky defect per 1016 ions.", "fibs": ["defect"]}
{"text": "Schottky defect is shown by ionic substances in which the cation and anion are of almost similar sizes.", "fibs": ["defect"]}
{"text": "For example, NaCl, KCl, CsCl and AgBr.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "It may be noted that AgBr shows both, Frenkel as well as Schottky defects.", "fibs": ["AgBr"]}
{"text": "(b) Impurity Defects
If molten NaCl containing a little amount of SrCl2 is crystallised, some of the sites of Na+ ions are occupied by Sr2+ (Fig.1.31).", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "It occupies the site of one ion and the other site remains vacant.", "fibs": ["site"]}
{"text": "The cationic vacancies thus produced are equal in number to that of Sr2+ ions.", "fibs": ["cationic"]}
{"text": "Another similar example is the solid solution of CdCl2 and AgCl.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.31: Introduction of cation vacancy in NaCl by substitution of Na+ by Sr2+

(c) Non-Stoichiometric Defects
The defects discussed so far do not disturb the stoichiometry of the crystalline substance.", "fibs": ["Introduction"]}
{"text": "However, a large number of non-stoichiometric inorganic solids are known which contain the constituent elements in non-stoichiometric ratio due to defects in their crystal structures.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "These defects are of two types: (i) metal excess defect and (ii) metal deficiency defect.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "(i) Metal Excess Defect


Fig.", "fibs": ["Defect"]}
{"text": "1.32: An F-centre in a crystal


Metal excess defect due to anionic vacancies: Alkali halides like NaCl and KCl show this type of defect.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "When crystals of NaCl are heated in an atmosphere of sodium vapour, the sodium atoms are deposited on the surface of the crystal.", "fibs": ["NaCl"]}
{"text": "The Cl– ions diffuse to the surface of the crystal and combine with Na atoms to give NaCl.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "This happens by loss of electron by sodium atoms to form Na+ ions.", "fibs": ["loss"]}
{"text": "The released electrons diffuse into the crystal and occupy anionic sites (Fig.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "As a result the crystal now has an excess of sodium.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "The anionic sites occupied by unpaired electrons are called F-centres (from the German word Farbenzenter for colour centre).", "fibs": ["word"]}
{"text": "They impart yellow colour to the crystals of NaCl.", "fibs": ["colour"]}
{"text": "The colour results by excitation of these electrons when they absorb energy from the visible light falling on the crystals.", "fibs": ["colour"]}
{"text": "Similarly, excess of lithium makes LiCl crystals pink and excess of potassium makes KCl crystals violet (or lilac).", "fibs": ["lithium"]}
{"text": "Metal excess defect due to the presence of extra cations at interstitial sites: Zinc oxide is white in colour at room temperature.", "fibs": ["defect"]}
{"text": "On heating it loses oxygen and turns yellow.", "fibs": ["heating"]}
{"text": "Now there is excess of zinc in the crystal and its formula becomes Zn1+xO.", "fibs": ["zinc"]}
{"text": "The excess Zn2+ ions move to interstitial sites and the electrons to neighbouring interstitial sites.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "(ii) Metal Deficiency Defect

There are many solids which are difficult to prepare in the stoichiometric composition and contain less amount of the metal as compared to the stoichiometric proportion.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "A typical example of this type is FeO which is mostly found with a composition of Fe0.95O.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "It may actually range from Fe0.93O to Fe0.96O.", "fibs": ["range"]}
{"text": "In crystals of FeO some Fe2+ cations are missing and the loss of positive charge is made up by the presence of required number of Fe3+ ions.", "fibs": ["FeO"]}
{"text": "1.10 Electrical Properties








Solids exhibit an amazing range of electrical conductivities, extending over 27 orders of magnitude ranging from 10–20 to 107 ohm–1 m–1.", "fibs": ["exhibit"]}
{"text": "Solids can be classified into three types on the basis of their conductivities.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
{"text": "(i) Conductors: The solids with conductivities ranging between 104 to 107 ohm–1m–1 are called conductors.", "fibs": ["ohm–1m–1"]}
{"text": "Metals have conductivities in the order of 107 ohm–1m–1 are good conductors.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "(ii) Insulators : These are the solids with very low conductivities ranging between 10–20 to 10–10 ohm–1m–1.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "(iii) Semiconductors : These are the solids with conductivities in the intermediate range from 10–6 to 104 ohm–1m–1.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "1.10.1 Conduction of Electricity in Metals
A conductor may conduct electricity through movement of electrons or ions.", "fibs": ["conductor"]}
{"text": "Metallic conductors belong to the former category and electrolytes to the latter.", "fibs": ["category"]}
{"text": "Metals conduct electricity in solid as well as molten state.", "fibs": ["conduct"]}
{"text": "The conductivity of metals depend upon the number of valence electrons available per atom.", "fibs": ["conductivity"]}
{"text": "The atomic orbitals of metal atoms form molecular orbitals which are so close in energy to each other as to form a band.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "If this band is partially filled or it overlaps with a higher energy unoccupied conduction band, then electrons can flow easily under an applied electric field and the metal shows conductivity (Fig.", "fibs": ["band"]}
{"text": "If the gap between filled valence band and the next higher unoccupied band (conduction band) is large, electrons cannot jump to it and such a substance has very small conductivity and it behaves as an insulator (Fig.", "fibs": ["gap"]}
{"text": "1.33 b).", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "1.10.2 Conduction of Electricity in Semi-conductors

In case of semiconductors, the gap between the valence band and conduction band is small (Fig.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Therefore, some electrons may jump to conduction band and show some conductivity.", "fibs": ["jump"]}
{"text": "Electrical conductivity of semiconductors increases with rise in temperature, since more electrons can jump to the conduction band.", "fibs": ["conductivity"]}
{"text": "Substances like silicon and germanium show this type of behaviour and are called intrinsic semiconductors.", "fibs": ["silicon"]}
{"text": "The conductivity of these intrinsic semiconductors is too low to be of practical use.", "fibs": ["conductivity"]}
{"text": "Their conductivity is increased by adding an appropriate amount of suitable impurity.", "fibs": ["conductivity"]}
{"text": "This process is called doping.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "Doping can be done with an impurity which is electron rich or electron deficient as compared to the intrinsic semiconductor silicon or germanium.", "fibs": ["impurity"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.33 Distinction among  (a) metals  (b) insulators and  (c) semiconductors.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "In each case, an unshaded area represents a conduction band.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "(a) Electron – rich impurities
Silicon and germanium belong to group 14 of the periodic table and have four valence electrons each.", "fibs": ["germanium"]}
{"text": "In their crystals each atom forms four covalent bonds with its neighbours (Fig.", "fibs": ["atom"]}
{"text": "When doped with a group 15 element like P or As, which contains five valence electrons, they occupy some of the lattice sites in silicon or germanium crystal (Fig.", "fibs": ["group"]}
{"text": "1.34 b).", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "Four out of five electrons are used in the formation of four covalent bonds with the four neighbouring silicon atoms.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "The fifth electron is extra and becomes delocalised.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "These delocalised electrons increase the conductivity of doped silicon (or germanium).", "fibs": ["increase"]}
{"text": "Here the increase in conductivity is due to the negatively charged electron, hence silicon doped with electron-rich impurity is called n-type semiconductor.", "fibs": ["increase"]}
{"text": "(b) Electron – deficit impurities


Silicon or germanium can also be doped with a group 13 element like B, Al or Ga which contains only three valence electrons.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "The place where the fourth valence electron is missing is called electron hole or electron vacancy (Fig.", "fibs": ["place"]}
{"text": "An electron from a neighbouring atom can come and fill the electron hole, but in doing so it would leave an electron hole at its original position.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "If it happens, it would appear as if the electron hole has moved in the direction opposite to that of the electron that filled it.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "Under the influence of electric field, electrons would move towards the positively charged plate through electronic holes, but it would appear as if electron holes are positively charged and are moving towards negatively charged plate.", "fibs": ["influence"]}
{"text": "This type of semi conductors are called p-type semiconductors.", "fibs": ["type"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "1.34: Creation of n-type and p-type semiconductors by doping groups 13 and 15 elements.", "fibs": ["Creation"]}
{"text": "Diode is a combination of n-type and p-type semiconductors and is used as a rectifier.", "fibs": ["combination"]}
{"text": "Transistors are made by sandwiching a layer of one type of semiconductor between two layers of the other type of semiconductor.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "npn and pnp type of transistors are used to detect or amplify radio or audio signals.", "fibs": ["npn"]}
{"text": "The solar cell is an efficient photo-diode used for conversion of light energy into electrical energy.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "Germanium and silicon are group 14 elements and therefore, have a characteristic valence of four and form four bonds as in diamond.", "fibs": ["Germanium"]}
{"text": "A large variety of solid state materials have been prepared by combination of groups 13 and 15 or 12 and 16 to simulate average valence of four as in Ge or Si.", "fibs": ["variety"]}
{"text": "Typical compounds of groups 13 – 15 are InSb, AlP and GaAs.", "fibs": ["InSb"]}
{"text": "Gallium arsenide (GaAs) semiconductors have very fast response and have revolutionised the design of semiconductor devices.", "fibs": ["Gallium"]}
{"text": "ZnS, CdS, CdSe and HgTe are examples of groups 12 – 16 compounds.", "fibs": ["ZnS"]}
{"text": "In these compounds, the bonds are not perfectly covalent and the ionic character depends on the electronegativities of the two elements.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "It is interesting to learn that transition metal oxides show marked differences in electrical properties.", "fibs": ["transition"]}
{"text": "TiO, CrO2 and ReO3 behave like metals.", "fibs": ["TiO"]}
{"text": "Rhenium oxide, ReO3 is like metallic copper in its conductivity and appearance.", "fibs": ["Rhenium"]}
{"text": "Certain other oxides like VO, VO2, VO3 and TiO3 show metallic or insulating properties depending on temperature.", "fibs": ["VO"]}
{"text": "1.11 Magnetic Properties




Every substance has some magnetic properties associated with it.", "fibs": ["substance"]}
{"text": "The origin of these properties lies in the electrons.", "fibs": ["origin"]}
{"text": "Each electron in an atom behaves like a tiny magnet.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "Its magnetic moment originates from two types of motions (i) its orbital motion around the nucleus and (ii) its spin around its own axis (Fig.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "Electron being a charged particle and undergoing these motions can be considered as a small loop of current which possesses a magnetic moment.", "fibs": ["particle"]}
{"text": "Thus, each electron has a permanent spin and an orbital magnetic moment associated with it.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "Magnitude of this magnetic moment is very small and is measured in the unit called Bohr magneton, µB.", "fibs": ["Magnitude"]}
{"text": "It is equal to 9.27 × 10–24A m2.", "fibs": ["×"]}
{"text": "Fig.1.35: Demonstration of the magnetic moment associated with (a) an orbiting electron and (b) a spinning electron.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "On the basis of their magnetic properties, substances can be classified into five categories: (i) paramagnetic (ii) diamagnetic (iii) ferromagnetic (iv) antiferromagnetic and (v) ferrimagnetic.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
{"text": "(i) Paramagnetism: Paramagnetic substances are weakly attracted by a magnetic field.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "They are magnetised in a magnetic field in the same direction.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "They lose their magnetism in the absence of magnetic field.", "fibs": ["magnetism"]}
{"text": "Paramagnetism is due to presence of one or more unpaired electrons which are attracted by the magnetic field.", "fibs": ["presence"]}
{"text": "(ii) Diamagnetism: Diamagnetic substances are weakly repelled by a magnetic field.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "H2O, NaCl and C6H6 are some examples of such substances.", "fibs": ["NaCl"]}
{"text": "They are weakly magnetised in a magnetic field in opposite direction.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Pairing of electrons cancels their magnetic moments and they lose their magnetic character.", "fibs": ["Pairing"]}
{"text": "(iii) Ferromagnetism: A few substances like iron, cobalt, nickel, gadolinium and CrO2 are attracted very strongly by a magnetic field.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "In solid state, the metal ions of ferromagnetic substances are grouped together into small regions called domains.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "Thus, each domain acts as a tiny magnet.", "fibs": ["domain"]}
{"text": "In an unmagnetised piece of a ferromagnetic substance the domains are randomly oriented and their magnetic moments get cancelled.", "fibs": ["piece"]}
{"text": "When the substance is placed in a magnetic field all the domains get oriented in the direction of the magnetic field (Fig.", "fibs": ["substance"]}
{"text": "1.36 a) and a strong magnetic effect is produced.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "This ordering of domains persist even when the magnetic field is removed and the ferromagnetic substance becomes a permanent magnet.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "(iv) Antiferromagnetism: Substances like MnO showing anti-ferromagnetism have domain structure similar to ferromagnetic substance, but their domains are oppositely oriented and cancel out each other’s magnetic moment (Fig.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "1.36 b).", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "(v) Ferrimagnetism: Ferrimagnetism is observed when the magnetic moments of the domains in the substance are aligned in parallel and anti-parallel directions in unequal numbers (Fig.", "fibs": ["v"]}
{"text": "1.36c).", "fibs": ["1.36c"]}
{"text": "They are weakly attracted by magnetic field as compared to ferromagnetic substances.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Fe3O4 (magnetite) and ferrites like MgFe2O4 and ZnFe2O4 are examples of such substances.", "fibs": ["magnetite"]}
{"text": "These substances also lose ferrimagnetism on heating and become paramagnetic.", "fibs": ["ferrimagnetism"]}
{"text": "Fig 1.36: Schematic alignment of magnetic moments in (a) ferromagnetic


(b) antiferromagnetic and (c) ferrimagnetic.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
